              <h2>How this Nova Scotia tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your 2025 income tax if you are a resident
                of Nova Scotia. It combines
                <strong>federal income tax</strong>,
                <strong>Nova Scotia provincial tax</strong>, and standard
                <strong>CPP</strong> and <strong>EI</strong> contributions to
                show your approximate <strong>net take‑home pay</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Federal income tax brackets (2025)</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator applies the Canadian federal tax brackets
                progressively to your taxable income:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>15% on the first federal bracket of taxable income</li>
                  <li>20.5% on the next bracket</li>
                  <li>26% on the next bracket</li>
                  <li>29% on the next bracket</li>
                  <li>33% on income above the top bracket threshold</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  It also subtracts the basic federal personal amount and any
                  extra non‑refundable credits you enter.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Nova Scotia provincial tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                Nova Scotia has its own set of progressive tax brackets. The
                calculator applies:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Brackets starting at the lowest provincial rate on your
                    first dollars of income
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Higher rates as your income moves into higher brackets
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  A provincial basic personal amount is also applied, plus any
                  additional credits you specify.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. CPP and EI contributions</h3>
              <p>
                If you leave the default options checked, the calculator
                estimates your mandatory payroll contributions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>CPP</strong> – a percentage of your employment income
                  between the yearly minimum and maximum pensionable earnings,
                  up to the annual CPP maximum.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>EI</strong> – a percentage of insurable earnings, up
                  to the annual EI maximum.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These amounts are <em>not</em> income tax, but they reduce your
                take‑home pay, so they are included in the “Total tax &amp;
                contributions” figure.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Effective tax rate</h3>
              <p>The effective tax rate shown is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  Effective tax rate = (Federal tax + Nova Scotia tax) ÷ Taxable
                  income
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is usually lower than your top marginal rate, because the
                first part of your income is taxed at lower bracket rates and
                reduced by personal amounts.
              </p>

              <h2>Nova Scotia HST explained</h2>
              <p>
                Nova Scotia uses a
                <strong>15% Harmonized Sales Tax (HST)</strong>, which combines
                the federal GST and the provincial sales tax. The HST calculator
                on this page simply multiplies your purchase amount by 15% and
                adds it to show the total cost.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  HST = Purchase amount × 0.15<br />
                  Total cost = Purchase amount + HST
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Some items may be <em>zero‑rated</em> or <em>exempt</em> from
                HST (for example, basic groceries or certain medical devices).
                Those special cases are not modeled here.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes you are a resident of Nova Scotia for the full tax
                  year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Focuses on employment and simple other income; does not model
                  complex business or investment structures.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Uses standard CPP/EI rates and maximums; actual payroll may
                  differ slightly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Only approximates non‑refundable credits via the “Additional
                  credits” field.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For official rates and detailed rules, always refer to the
                <a
                  href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency.html"
                  rel="nofollow"
                  >Canada Revenue Agency (CRA)</a
                >
                and the
                <a href="https://novascotia.ca" rel="nofollow"
                  >Government of Nova Scotia</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What taxes does this Nova Scotia tax calculator include?</h3>
              <p>
                It includes estimated 2025 federal income tax, Nova Scotia
                provincial income tax, CPP, EI, and your net take‑home pay. It
                also provides a separate HST calculator for purchases.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for self‑employment income?</h3>
              <p>
                You can enter self‑employment income as “other taxable income”
                for a rough estimate, but the calculator does not handle all
                self‑employment deductions, instalments, or special CPP rules.
                For accurate results, speak with an accountant or use CRA tools
                designed for self‑employed individuals.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this an official Nova Scotia or CRA calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an independent educational tool. It is designed to
                be as accurate as reasonably possible using current public tax
                parameters, but it is not a substitute for professional advice
                or official government calculators.
              </p>
